  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Selling a property as part of a deceased estate is one of the more complex transactions an executor will navigate, particularly during what is already a difficult period. The sale itself, once the legal requirements are in place, is not dramatically different from any other property sale. The complexity lies in what needs to happen before the estate can legally deal with the property, how to manage the interests of multiple beneficiaries, and what the tax implications look like for the estate and its beneficiaries.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is probate and when is it required?</h2>
      <p>Probate is the legal process by which a court confirms the validity of a deceased person's will and the authority of the executor named in that will to administer the estate. In Queensland, the Supreme Court grants probate, and once it is granted, the executor has the legal authority to deal with the estate's assets, including real property.</p>

      <p>Whether probate is required before a property can be sold depends on how the property is held. If the property was held in the deceased's name alone (as a sole owner or as a tenant in common), probate is generally required before the property can be transferred to a buyer or to a beneficiary. If the property was held as joint tenants with a surviving co-owner, the survivor's interest passes automatically by survivorship and probate is typically not required for that transfer, though the surviving joint tenant will need to lodge a Transmission by Death application with the Queensland titles registry.</p>

      <p>If the deceased did not leave a valid will, the estate is said to be intestate. In that case, an eligible person (usually a spouse or adult child) can apply to the court for Letters of Administration, which serve a similar function to probate: they give the administrator legal authority to deal with the estate's assets. The timeline for Letters of Administration is typically longer than for probate because the court needs to be satisfied about the applicant's entitlement to administer the estate.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The executor's authority to sell</h2>
      <p>Once probate or Letters of Administration has been granted, the executor or administrator has the authority to sell real property on behalf of the estate. The executor acts in a fiduciary capacity: they are not selling their own property, but administering the estate for the benefit of the beneficiaries. This distinction has practical consequences for how the sale is conducted.</p>

      <p>The executor must act in the best interests of all beneficiaries and is legally required to achieve a proper price for the property. This does not mean they must accept the highest offer in every circumstance, but it does mean they cannot sell at a significant undervalue, even if it would be more convenient or expedient to do so. If an executor sells at below market value without proper justification, beneficiaries have grounds to challenge the sale and seek compensation from the executor personally.</p>

      <p>For this reason, most executors arrange for a formal market appraisal from a licensed real estate agent, and sometimes a formal valuation from a registered valuer, before they set the asking price or accept an offer. This provides a documented basis for the price achieved and protects the executor from later claims that the property was undersold.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the estate sale process differs from a standard sale</h2>
      <p>In most respects, marketing and selling a deceased estate property follows the same process as any other sale: preparation, photography, advertising, open homes, offers, contract, and settlement. The differences are mostly procedural and legal rather than practical.</p>

      <p>The contract will be signed by the executor in their capacity as executor of the estate, rather than by the seller personally. The contract title line will typically read something like "John Smith as executor of the estate of Mary Smith deceased." This is important: a contract signed in the wrong capacity, or before probate is granted, may not be binding or may need to be re-executed once probate is obtained. Your solicitor should review the contract and the signing arrangements before exchange.</p>

      <p>Settlement can also be more complex than a standard sale. The proceeds from the sale must flow into the estate's account and be distributed in accordance with the will and the executor's obligations to the beneficiaries. If there are outstanding debts, mortgages, or claims against the estate, these may need to be resolved at or before settlement. Your solicitor will handle the settlement adjustments, but the executor should be aware that a simple bank transfer of proceeds is rarely the final step.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The timeline from death to settlement</h2>
      <p>One of the most common frustrations executors experience is the time it takes between a person's death and the point at which the property can be settled with a buyer. The timeline depends on several factors, but it is rarely as short as executors hope at the outset.</p>

      <p>The probate application itself can take anywhere from four to twelve weeks after death, depending on the complexity of the estate, the availability of required documents, and the court's current processing times. More complex estates, disputed wills, or applications that are not properly prepared can take significantly longer. While the probate application is being processed, the executor cannot legally execute a binding contract of sale, which means the property cannot formally be sold.</p>

      <p>However, it is common practice for executors to begin the marketing campaign before probate is granted, with any contracts made conditional on probate being obtained. This allows the campaign to run in parallel with the probate application, which can reduce the overall timeline considerably. Your agent and solicitor should discuss this approach if it is appropriate for your situation.</p>

      <p>Once probate is granted and a contract is signed, the settlement period is typically 30 to 60 days, in line with standard Queensland property transactions. The total timeline from death to settlement proceeds in the estate's hands can range from three months in straightforward cases to twelve months or more in complex or contested situations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Multiple beneficiaries and the risk of disputes</h2>
      <p>When there are multiple beneficiaries with an interest in the estate, the sale of a property can become a point of conflict, even in families that are otherwise functioning well. One beneficiary may want to keep the property. Another may need their share of the proceeds quickly. A third may believe the property could achieve a higher price if sold differently or at a different time. These competing interests are the executor's challenge to manage.</p>

      <p>The executor's legal obligation is to the estate as a whole, not to any individual beneficiary. If one beneficiary disagrees with the executor's decision to sell, or with the price accepted, they can raise that concern with the executor. If they believe the executor is acting improperly, they can apply to the court for review. In practice, most disputes are resolved through clear communication from the executor about the basis for their decisions, rather than through litigation.</p>

      <p>Executors who keep beneficiaries informed, document the basis for their decisions, and act transparently throughout the process are much less likely to face a formal dispute. If the family dynamic suggests that conflict is likely, engaging a solicitor to manage all beneficiary communications from the outset is worth considering.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">CGT implications for deceased estates</h2>
      <p>Capital gains tax is a significant consideration in deceased estate sales and is handled differently from CGT on a standard investment property sale. The rules are set by the Australian Tax Office and are technical, so this is an area where you should take advice from an accountant or tax adviser who is familiar with estate taxation, not just general property tax.</p>

      <p>The key rules as they apply in most Queensland deceased estate situations: when a person dies, the property is deemed to have been acquired by the beneficiary or estate at the deceased's date of death. The cost base of the property for CGT purposes is generally the market value at the date of death, not the original purchase price paid by the deceased. This means the estate or beneficiary pays CGT only on the growth in value from the date of death to the date of sale, not on the full gain over the deceased's entire ownership period.</p>

      <p>There is also a 12-month rule worth noting: if the property is sold within 12 months of the deceased's death, the full CGT on any gain is payable by the estate. If the property is sold more than 12 months after death, the estate is entitled to the 50 per cent CGT discount on any capital gain, in the same way that an individual who has owned a property for more than 12 months is entitled to the discount.</p>

      <p>If the property was the deceased's main residence and meets the main residence exemption criteria, it may be fully or partially exempt from CGT, depending on when and how it was used. This exemption has time limits and conditions that your accountant should confirm before settlement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to present and market a deceased estate honestly</h2>
      <p>Deceased estate properties are often presented in the condition in which the previous owner lived, which can range from impeccably maintained to requiring significant work. The honest approach is to present the property accurately: do not overclaim condition, do not hide known defects, and do not over-style a property to obscure issues that a building inspection will reveal.</p>

      <p>Many deceased estate buyers expect some degree of work to be required and price accordingly. A property that is honestly presented, cleanly cleared of personal belongings, and professionally photographed will attract genuine buyers. Buyers who feel they have been misled about condition withdraw from contracts and leave bad reviews. This is a reputational risk the estate does not need.</p>

      <p>In some cases, a modest investment in cleaning, painting, and garden clearing before listing can meaningfully improve presentation without overclaiming condition. Your agent can advise on what is worth doing and what is not, based on comparable sales and the likely buyer profile for your property.</p>

